The Data

Our Approach

It would be difficult to provide a comprehensive analysis of all the factors considered in property aquisition, so we took three overarching considerations (price, size, and location), and expanded them into five factors we analyse to help you determine the best area in London for you to buy or invest in a property.

  1. Price
    • To help you find a reasonably priced, in-budget home.
  2. Number of Bedrooms
    • If your family is large, or is planning on growing, or if you simply like the space.
  3. Air Quality
    • Who doesn't love fresh air.
  4. Crime Rate
    • Pick a neighbourhood where the only break-ins involve stealing your heart, not your stuff.
  5. Distance from the Centre of London
    • Life's too short to spend it stuck in traffic.

Data Sources

Our primary data souce is RightMove, as they hold a substancial amount of data on sold properties, including properties' price history and details all of the ammenities (number of bedrooms, bathrooms, and occasionally square footage). In addition to this, we require data on air quality and crime rates, gained through the Google API and PlumPlot respectively.

  • House Prices and Number of Bedrooms
  • Air Quality
  • Crime Rate

Our Analysis

Our analysis considers the data which directly affects house prices, as well as data which does not have a large effect on property value but does impact standards of living. This allowed us to strive for cheap prices while maximizing quality, hence achieving a ranking which calculates, what we think, represents value for money.

To do this, we first took the most impactful variables we've pulled and calculated their impact on house pricing, thus allowing us to consider their impact on value for money. We then took these variables and displayed them in heat maps, this visualized areas which excelled and allows users to see where in London is best suited to their specific requirements if they have concerns about specific factors. Penultimately, we created an overall ranking, taking every listing on Right Move and indexing them by our opinion of value for money via a weighted formula. We realized that everyone is looking for different qualities when buying a house, which is why our final function involved allowing the user to conduct their own analysis. For this, we created an interactive table, giving the user a chance to enter in the metrics they are looking for, which we then took to create a bespoke table of properties which cater to their requirements. We also created some visualization of house price inflation, an important consideration for buying or renting which wasn't included in our synopsis due to us wanting to provide a 'snap shot' of the current market'

Correlation Analysis

It is important to determine the correlation and variance within our data. We needed to see how our variables impacted price as this allows us to predict what a house meeting certain quality thresholds might cost. It can also indicate what current considerations play a role in dictating the property market, hence showing us what is important to buyers.

display(pd.read_csv('Data/display/correlation_table'))
Unnamed: 0 Correlation with Price Variance
0 Number of Bedrooms 0.345345 1.693430
1 crime rate -0.170161 74.836127
2 AQI 0.022040 39.962825
3 Distance from Center of London -0.280540 36.859949
4 Overall Rating 0.304088 153.363383

This shows that the number of bedrooms has the biggest impact on price, with a low variance meaning we're unlikely to find many exceptions to this rule. Additionally, crime rate and distance from the centre of London have a negative correlation, meaning as they increase, price is likely to drop. This is expected but the high variance shows there's many exceptions to this rule which we will hope to seek out. AQI has a very weak correlation indicating it doesn't durastically effect house prices. This makes sense due to it not being a normal consideration when purchasing a house and it means we should be able to achieve a high air quality index when filtering through our listings to find value for money.

# setting up to show graph
df_normalise = pd.read_csv('Data/display/normalise.csv')
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import plotly.express as px
import numpy as np

# group by data and calculate the mean price for each category
avg_price_by_bedrooms = df_normalise.groupby('num_bedrooms')['price_not_normalised'].mean().reset_index()
avg_price_by_crime = df_normalise.groupby('crime rate')['price_not_normalised'].mean().reset_index()
avg_price_by_AQI = df_normalise.groupby('AQI')['price_not_normalised'].mean().reset_index()
avg_price_by_dist = df_normalise.groupby('central dist')['price_not_normalised'].mean().reset_index()

# create tge line graph
fig = px.line()

# add the variable, price line to the graph
fig.add_scatter(x=avg_price_by_bedrooms['num_bedrooms'], y=avg_price_by_bedrooms['price_not_normalised'], mode='lines', name='Bedrooms')
fig.add_scatter(x=avg_price_by_crime['crime rate'], y=avg_price_by_crime['price_not_normalised'], mode='lines', name='Crime Rate')
fig.add_scatter(x=avg_price_by_AQI['AQI'], y=avg_price_by_AQI['price_not_normalised'], mode='lines', name='AQI')

# creating a line of best fit for distance from center 
slope, intercept = np.polyfit(avg_price_by_dist['central dist'], avg_price_by_dist['price_not_normalised'], 1)
line_trace = go.Scatter(x=avg_price_by_dist['central dist'], y=slope * avg_price_by_dist['central dist'] + intercept + 200000, mode='lines', name='dist from center (best fit)', line=dict(color='blue'))
fig.add_trace(line_trace)


# finish layout
fig.update_layout(title='Variables effect on price', xaxis_title='As variable increases from lowest to highest value', yaxis_title='Price (£)')
fig.update_yaxes(range=[0, 8000000])
fig.show()

Using Plotly, we created this graph to visualize the relationship and allow users to see more detail of the relationship, instead of an overview. We normalized the data using a MinMax scalar so they could all be shown using the same index and grouped the data by mean against house price to achieve lines instead of a scatter plot.

  • We can see the minimal variation for bedrooms because of the smooth line, meaning it's very hard to get lots of bedrooms for a cheap price. We also see a drop in bedrooms impact on price towards the end, indicating that beyond a certain point, people may not want an excessive number of rooms.

  • It shows a lot of variation for crime rate with more variation for low crime areas. This indicates that, while low crime areas are generally more expensive, it's still possible to get low crime at a low price.

  • Air Quality Index doesn't appear to be impactful on price at any stage apart from the best air quality. This means we can get very good air quality for a low price, but to achieve optimal AQI you may need to spend a bit more.

  • For distance from the center we decided to use a line of best fit as better showed the relationship between price and distance. As shown, the further from London's center, the cheaper the property.

Individual Variable Analysis

Buyers may have specific concerns about individual factors when buying a house so we decided to create heat maps of crime rates and AQI. From these, a potential buyer can see areas which best cater to their needs and make decisions from there. It also allows a property stake holder to see the surrounding area of their property, a concern for people who tend to spend time outside their house in the local area.

For these heat maps we used folium to generate a map centered around London. We then added heat metrics using the data we had accumulated and adjusted the parameters to optimize interpretability.

Crime Rate Analysis

listing_data = pd.read_csv('Data/primary/all_listing_data.csv')
import folium
from folium.plugins import HeatMap


# generate a map centered around London
heat_data = list(zip(listing_data['latitude'], listing_data['longitude'], listing_data['crime rate']))

# creating a map of London
map_london = folium.Map(location=[51.509865, -0.118092], zoom_start=11)

# adding heat map to the map, using the 'display_price' column as weights
HeatMap(heat_data, min_opacity=0.2, radius=16, blur=16, max_zoom=1).add_to(map_london)

display(map_london)
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

This shows crime 'hotspots' around London but generally towards the center. This makes sense as the center has more foot traffic and a higher population density so would naturally have higher crime rates. Therefore, if you are trying to avoid crime, you may choose to live further out in London.

Air Quality Analysis

# generate a map centered around London

# creating a map of London
map_london = folium.Map(location=[51.509865, -0.118092], zoom_start=11)

Air pollution is higher in central and west London. For better air quality, someone would be better suited to live in North West or South East.

Are You Getting Value for Your Money?

Calculating value for money was our way of determining the 'best' places to live in London. We wanted to rank properties on Right Move by bang for buck and to do this we had to incorporate all our findings into a comprehensive index. For this, we considered the importance of each variable, how they affect one another, and how we can manage to keep prices as low as possible when choosing these ideal houses. Our result was a complete ranking of all properties we pulled given a rating from 0-100. We used normalized data so larger numbers wouldn't crowd out the impact of smaller metrics and ran each listing through the chosen formula to achieve the Overall Ranking.

The weights we came up with were: |Variable| Weight| Justification | |---|---|---| |House Price:| -0.9| keep prices low without sacrificing quality| |Number of Bedrooms:| 0.7| Indicates size of house| |Crime Rate:| -0.5|Keep high ranking houses in safe areas| |Air Quality Index:| 0.4|Indicates low traffic area and healthier| |Distance From Center:| -0.6|Closer to employment and entertainment|


The Fomula

$ Overall ranking = House Price * -0.9 + Number of Bedrooms * 0.7 + Crime Rate * -0.5 + Air Quality Index * 0.4 + Distance From Center * -0.6 $

Examples of properties that did well on our ranking:

Failures of the Formula

Our formula does have downfalls, such as:

  • Properties with lots of bedrooms failing to be filtered out.
  • It doesn't account for the Tenure type (Freehold being favourable).
  • We can't asses the condition of the house.
  • Some high cost properties score highly if they excel in other areas.

A Bespoke Analysis

Ultimately, everyone has their own considerations when looking for a property. This is why we created an interactive app component with Dash (plotly extension) which allows users to customize their searching experience, thus finding the best property listings for their needs.

listing_data = pd.read_csv('Data/primary/final_rating.csv')


# requires 'pip install dash' in the terminal
from dash import Dash, dcc, html, dash_table
from dash.dependencies import Input, Output

# deleting columns from table that make it look messy when visualizing
del listing_data['property_type']
del listing_data['latitude']
del listing_data['longitude']
del listing_data['Unnamed: 0']
del listing_data['has_floor_plan']
del listing_data['date_sold']
del listing_data['url']
del listing_data['postcode']

# making remaining data look more clean
listing_data['crime rate'] = listing_data['crime rate'].round(2)
listing_data['rating'] = listing_data['rating'].round(2)

# create a Dash web application
app = Dash(__name__)

# define the layout of the web application
app.layout = html.Div([
    html.H1("Interactive House Listing Table"),
    
    # dropdown for selecting number of bedrooms
    dcc.Dropdown(
        id='bedroom-dropdown',
        options=[{'label': str(i), 'value': i} for i in range(1, 10)],
        value=None,
        placeholder="Select number of bedrooms"
    ),
    
    # dropdown for maximum price
    dcc.Dropdown(
        id='price-dropdown',
        options=[{'label': str(i), 'value': i} for i in range(0, 8000000, 100000)],
        value=None,
        placeholder="Select maximum price"
    ),
    
    # dropdown for selecting minimum AQI
    dcc.Dropdown(
    id='aqi-dropdown',
    options=[{'label': str(i), 'value': i} for i in range(60, 101)], 
    value=None,
    placeholder="Select minimum AQI"
    ),
    
    # dropdown for maximum crime rate
    dcc.Dropdown(
        id='crime-dropdown',
        options=[{'label': str(i), 'value': i} for i in range(0, 100, 10)],
        value=None,
        placeholder="Select maximum crime rate (per 1000)"
    ),
    
    # dropdown for maximum distance from center of London
    dcc.Dropdown(
        id='distance-dropdown',
        options=[{'label': str(i), 'value': i} for i in range(0, 50, 1)],
        value=None,
        placeholder="Select maximum distance from center (km)"
    ),
    
    # creating output table
    dash_table.DataTable(id='listing-table'),
])

# define callback to update the table based on user input
@app.callback(
    Output('listing-table', 'data'),
    [Input('bedroom-dropdown', 'value'),
     Input('price-dropdown', 'value'),
     Input('aqi-dropdown', 'value'),
     Input('crime-dropdown', 'value'),
     Input('distance-dropdown', 'value')]
)
def update_table(selected_bedrooms, max_price, min_aqi, max_crime, max_distance):
    # filter the data based on user input
    filtered_data = listing_data

    if selected_bedrooms is not None:
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['num_bedrooms'] == selected_bedrooms]

    if max_price is not None:
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['display_price'] <= max_price]

    if min_aqi is not None:
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['AQI'] >= min_aqi]

    if max_crime is not None:
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['crime rate'] <= max_crime]

    if max_distance is not None:
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['central dist'] <= max_distance]

    # convert filtered data to dictionary format for DataTable
    table_data = filtered_data.to_dict('records')

    return table_data

# registering user input
def update_table(selected_bedrooms, max_price, min_aqi, max_crime, max_distance):
    # filter the data based on user input
    filtered_data = listing_data[
        (listing_data['num_bedrooms'] == selected_bedrooms if selected_bedrooms else True) &
        (listing_data['display_price'] <= max_price if max_price else True) &
        (listing_data['AQI'] >= min_aqi if min_aqi else True) &
        (listing_data['crime rate'] <= max_crime if max_crime else True) &
        (listing_data['central dist'] <= max_distance if max_distance else True)
    ]

    # convert filtered data to dictionary format for DataTable
    table_data = filtered_data.to_dict('records')

    return table_data

# run web application (may need to change port if it is already in use)
app.run_server(debug=True, port=8051)

Inflation Analysis

We also thought it was important to look at inflation when determining houses. This is useful as it gives a rough indication of how the house price might increase in the future for people buying property as an investment and for people hoping to rent, as this could lead to higher prices in the future.

from plotnine import *
df_expanded = pd.read_csv('Data/secondary/df_expanded.csv')
df_expanded['date_sold'] = pd.to_datetime(df_expanded['date_sold'])
plot = (
    ggplot(df_expanded, aes(x='date_sold', y='display_price', color='num_bedrooms')) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color='blue', se=False) +
    # xlim('1995-01-01', '2023-12-01') +  
    ylim(0, 2000000) +
    labs(title='Display Prices Under 2 Million Since 1995', x='Date Sold', y='Display Price (£)') +
    theme_minimal()+
    theme(figure_size=(8, 6))
)

display(plot)

This graph shows every listing of property on Right Move over the last 30 years and the number of bedrooms it has. It gives a useful representation of inflation and visualizes how higher bedroom properties reach higher prices (seen by lighter colors towards the top). We also created a heat map, indicating annual house price inflation in different areas of London. Users can refer to this to see if they are likely to have the house price increase rapidly or slowly over time which determines if it's a good or bad area to invest in.

The Formula

((ChangeInPrice)/(ChangeInTime)/365) * 100

# creating inflation data frame
inflation = df_expanded[['address', 'display_price', 'date_sold', 'latitude', 'longitude']]
df_expanded['date_sold'] = pd.to_datetime(df_expanded['date_sold'])

# cleaning and sorting
inflation = inflation.drop_duplicates()
inflation = inflation[inflation['address'].duplicated(keep=False)]
inflation = inflation.sort_values(by=['address', 'date_sold'])
inflation = inflation.groupby('address').filter(lambda x: len(x) <= 2)
inflation = inflation.assign(**inflation.groupby('address')[['display_price', 'date_sold']].diff())
inflation = inflation.dropna()

# applying simple inflation formula
inflation['inflation'] = ((inflation['display_price'] / (inflation['date_sold'].dt.days).astype(int)) / 365 * 100).round(2)

# creating a heat map showing inflation
map_london = folium.Map(location=[51.509865, -0.118092], zoom_start=11)
heat_data = list(zip(inflation['latitude'], inflation['longitude'], inflation['inflation']))

# adding heat map weighted by price
HeatMap(heat_data, 
        min_opacity=0.15,            
        radius=19,                  
        blur=2,                    
        max_zoom=1).add_to(map_london)

display(map_london)
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

It shows that inflation is prominent throughout London, with central London generally having very high levels of annual inflation and some outer areas having the lowest levels over the last 30 years.
